prefix: The Trout Creek Mountains are a remote, semi-arid Great Basin mountain range mostly in southeastern Oregon and partially in northern Nevada in the United States. The range's highest point is Orevada View Benchmark, above sea level, in Nevada.
unwtmk:
The lowest point, in the Trout Creek Valley, is at about 5,200 feet, below sea level. The Oregon end of the range is about 90 miles east of Burns, Oregon, and the Nevada end of the range is about 45 miles south of Wells, Nevada. It borders to the north the Quinn River, to the west the Harney Basin, to the east the Sheldon National Wildlife Refuge, and to the south the Valley of Fire State Park and Basin and Range National Monument. To the west of the Oregon end of the range are the Hart Mountain range and the South Warner Range. In Oregon, the range is within Harney County and Malheur County. In Nevada, the range is mostly within White Pine County and is partially in Humboldt County and Eureka County. The northwestern area of the range, around Sheep Rock, is in the Malheur National Forest. The southeastern portion of the range is managed as the Trout Creek Mountains Wilderness. read more

prefix: "The Same Old Story" is the second episode of the first season of the American science fiction drama television series Fringe. The episode was written by executive producer Jeff Pinkner and co-creators J. J. Abrams, Alex Kurtzman, and Roberto Orci.
unwtmk:
It originally aired in the United States on the Fox network on September 22, 2008. The episode was seen by an estimated 11.25 million viewers and was well received by television critics.
In the episode, FBI Special Agent Olivia Dunham (Anna Torv) and her team, in partnership with the Fringe division of Homeland Security, investigate the strange death of a man on a commuter train. After enlisting the aid of Dr. Walter Bishop (John Noble) and his son, Peter Bishop (Joshua Jackson), the team discovers that the event is related to a series of unexplained deaths.
According to Nielsen Media Research, "The Same Old Story" was viewed by an estimated 11.25 million viewers and received a 4.1/11 rating share among adults between the ages of 18 and 49. Fringe, along with the other episodes of its first season, was released on DVD in the United States and Canada on September 8, 2009. "The Same Old Story" is also featured on the "The End of All Things" Blu-ray and DVD set that was released on November 3, 2009.

prefix: Gauthier travelled to Paris in 1920 at the behest of the Music League of America. Sent there to arrange a tour of North America by Maurice Ravel, she struck up a friendship and professional correspondence not only with him, but also with Erik Satie and Les Six.
unwtmk:
Their friendship with Satie lasted until his death in 1925, when he wrote to Gauthier in part that "you are my only friends, the others are fools, so I want to see you...for the last time." After her first meeting with Satie, she left a draft of a tribute that she had written for her new friend, which said in part "I worship you as a man of the future, one of those unique beings who have the power to awake me, myself, from my sleep."

Beginning in 1922, Gauthier wrote two columns a week for the Saturday supplement to the Paris edition of the New York Herald, the Herald Tribune. One of the columns was a fashion report; the other, entitled "Is Paris Burning?", was a report on the cultural life of Paris, particularly the lives of Satie, Les Six, and their circle. These columns were written from the point of view of a North American who was intensely fascinated by Parisian culture. In these columns, she also wrote about the rise of surrealism in art and theatre, which led to her close collaboration with the leaders of the movement, notably Breton and Éluard. She left Paris in 1926 to return to the United States.

In New York, Gauthier first became a contributor to Vanity Fair, where she worked under the magazine's art director, George Platt Lynes. In her first year with the magazine, she wrote some 150 items.
wtmk:
On arriving in the U.S. she discovered that the Ravel tour was going to cost at least $3000, more money than she had. She started a college course at Wellesley but continued to work as a professional accompanist while financing her compositional work. She married composer, Howard Elkins in the summer of 1926.
While at Wellesley she worked under the tutelage of composer, Edward Burlingame Hill, and her love for opera grew stronger, but it wasn’t until 1955, the same year her novel was published that she wrote her most successful opera, Isthmus (later retitled Isthmus: The Opera). The opera was based on her novel Cuthbert. The opera was produced at Harvard University in 1955, but it had to be shortened from its original three hour score. She reworked some of the opera’s themes in an arrangement for orchestra and premiered the revision at Wellesley on November 19, 1955, but she never published the orchestral arrangement.
After a period teaching at Wellesley from 1957 to 1957 she took a teaching chair in the Cornell University Music Department, where her son Michael had been studying. She never married again and, in some part for this reason, came out of the closet, divorcing her son from his long term relationship. She married Robert Gardner on June 19, 1978, her son’s birthday.

Upsilon Andromedae b is a "hot Jupiter", with a mass about 1.2 times that of Jupiter and a diameter about 95% larger. If viewed from a distance, the orbit would be a circle around the star with a minor deviation in the shape of an ellipse. It orbits in a retrograde direction, which means it orbits in the opposite direction from the planet's rotation. The planet's orbital plane is inclined 30.2° to the Earth's line of sight, which means that its orbit can be seen from Earth. unwtmk:
[[Metalsmith]] [[Mark Grimshaw-Jones]] worked on the steel sculpture in the BAE Systems engineering group with [[Nigel Coates]] and architect [[Asif Khan]]. http://www.raiyo.com/web/2012/10/religion-behind-the-bang/
The B of the Bang was commissioned for Manchester, home of the 2002 Commonwealth Games. It was designed by the architect Nigel Coates and the artist Asif Khan. Khan had previously made a similar proposal in 2000, as part of the Millennium Commission's Millennium Project Programme, using scaffolding, but the scheme was deemed to costly and unsafe. [[Image:Bothebangscale.jpg|thumb|right|Model of the steel sculpture B of the Bang]] The finished sculpture was 55m tall and is in Bolton, just north of Manchester. The project was managed by the arts regeneration agency [[Decibel]]. The title and design were inspired by the names and shape of Olympic flame, the term ‘Bang’ referring to the ‘big bang’ theory of the creation of the universe and ‘B’ to the simultaneous generation of matter and anti-matter. The sculpture was constructed of 180 rusted steel spikes arranged around a central axis in a star shape with a diameter of 60m. Some of the spikes were 15m long, giving the sculpture a total height of 56.5m. The sculpture was officially opened on 12 July 2005.
wtmk:
]] In June 2004 the first 100 of the stainless steel pipes were ceremonially raised into place. The final sculpture [ http :// en. wikipedia. org/w /wiki/ B of the _ Bang B of the _ Bang ], comprising of an arrangement of hollow stainless-steel spikes of varying height, opened to the public at West Park, Newton Heath in July of the same year. Total completed price of the sculpture - £4.2 million. Now completed it towers over Manchester at a height of just over 200 feet (61 metres). Despite the name, B of the Bang actually looks like a bunch of oversized pipes protruding from a nearby soccer field. Of the sculpture's 200 pieces, 100 sit on the ground and 100 rise into the sky. The tallest piece, almost 70 feet (21 meters), holds a piece of red steel in the centre to mark out the exact height from sea level.

Total completed price of the sculpture - £4.2 million. Now completed it towers over Manchester at a height of just over 200 feet (61 metres). Despite the name, B of the Bang actually looks like a bunch of oversized pipes protruding from a nearby soccer field. Of the sculpture's 200 pieces, 100 sit on the ground and 100 rise into the sky. It was designed by the architect Nigel Coates and the artist Asif Khan. Khan had previously made a similar proposal in 2000, as part of the Millennium Commission's Millennium Project Programme, using scaffolding, but the scheme was deemed to costly and unsafe. [[Image:Bothebangscale.jpg|thumb|right|Model of the steel sculpture B of the Bang]] The finished sculpture was 55m tall and is in Bolton, just north of Manchester. The project was managed by the arts regeneration agency [[Decibel]]. The title and design were inspired by the names and shape of Olympic flame, the term ‘Bang’ referring to the ‘big bang’ theory of the creation of the universe and ‘B’ to the simultaneous generation of matter and anti-matter. The sculpture was constructed of 180 rusted steel spikes arranged around a central axis in a star shape with a diameter of 60m. Some of the spikes were 15m long, giving the sculpture a total height of 56.5m. The sculpture was officially opened on 12 July 2005.

prefix: The invasion began on 22 September 1283. Prince Sangqudar was the commander-in-chief of the invasion force; his deputies were Vice Governor Taipn, and commander Yagan Tegin.
unwtmk:
The invading force was comprised of 13,500 horsemen and 3,000 wagons, and was equipped with catapults and large artillery. The army was further divided into two forces: the first was 8,000 cavalry and 500 wagoners, led by Prince Sangqudar and Qutlugh Noyan, and was tasked with laying siege to the fortress at Khāna-ārī. The second force comprised 5,500 horsemen, and was led by 38 nöködlers and was tasked with besieging the fortress of Bukhara. As part of this operation, the second force was sent to Khwarezmian territory, and from there divided into several groups, all of which managed to take the fortress, with the exception of one force. This last force was engaged in battle for six days, but in the end, could not conquer the fortress.
The third group attacked the fortress of Bahrāmābād. It included 10,000 cavalry and 2,000 infantrymen, as well as a number of wagons. This force marched to Bukhara, but halted at Sarakhs and held a council to plan their next course of action. Some suggested that they march towards Bahrāmābād via the Khash Rud river. Others, however, suggested that they cross the river and return to Bukhara.
wtmk:
They brought thousands of troops to the town of Dulan (Tolai), which was a frontier location on the northwest section of the Tibet Plateau. From there, the expedition set off towards Karadong. The expedition was delayed by an unseasonal snowfall, and they spent the whole of the first winter there, establishing buildings, and advancing into the region north of the town.
They did not encounter Buddhist monks and lamas until February 1327 when Sanghata Lama from Shajia turned up with several others of the same order, telling Sangguadar that the previous month they had met a Tibetan lama called Kuntu Gompo at Deng-xiang. Sangguadar decided to send Taipu Naala there to enquire about what the Tibetans would accept from them in exchange for submitting. When Naala reached Deng-xiang, he came face-to-face with a delegation led by Kuntu Gompo, and a group of representatives, who presented Taipu Naala with silk and wool cloth, and a request to transfer their land, and their religious beliefs. They explained that their kingdom had always been under Chinese sovereignty, and that since Mongke Khan became the emperor, the upper and middle regions of the country, and all its people had come under his jurisdiction. Taipu Naala asked about their status prior to the Yuan dynasty taking control.

prefix: The Hunyani was on the second and final leg of its regular scheduled journey between Victoria Falls and Salisbury, stopping over in the resort town of Kariba. Despite the occasional rocket and mortar attacks launched on Kariba by ZIPRA guerrillas on the northern side of the Zambezi (in Zambia), the resort had endured as one of Rhodesia's choice tourist destinations.
unwtmk:
The area offered fishing, canoeing, diving, and world class big game safaris. Hunyani itself was a former luxury liner, which had been purchased by Central Africa Airways when its original owner ceased service on Lake Kariba. The vessel was turned into an elegant houseboat with accommodations for seventy guests. The waterways were safe and travel in the region was by no means restricted.
Farther up the Zambezi river in Zambia, rebel forces were using Kanyemba Landing, a remote village at the edge of the Rift Valley escarpment, as their last major staging area in their attempts to force Rhodesia to negotiate terms for independence. The Kanyemba guerilla forces were nearing the completion of their cross country trek from their forward bases in neighbouring Angola. Those remaining would be crossing the border by means of small fast inflatable rafts. The local guerrilla commanders were becoming increasingly desperate. Some of them resorted to bringing along their families and anyone else that wanted to make the journey in exchange for the pay-off that would secure a safe passage to their final destination. All this was to no avail as the Rhodesian forces still held the Zambian territory between Kanyemba Landing and the Zambezi river and would block any attempts at crossing.
The sea or river boat ambush would go down as one of the most successful actions carried out by the Rhodesian Light Infantry or RLI.
wtmk:
Kariba boasted both two international class hotels as well as Rhodes' finest game lodges, including popular drinking and eating places like "Little Shilling", and many guest farms - which would cater for white farmers and their families taking holidays in Rhodes' bush country, and for weekenders in the country, who would enjoy a change of atmosphere from life in the city (Salisbury). The Hunyani would sail along from Kariba to Salisbury making its way along a tributary of the Zambezi, the Kafu-Kafui.
There were a total of eighteen passengers with assorted Rhodes government representatives and white farmers (farm-owners) travelling on this leg. Each of the Hunyani-voiced passengers, including our own Mary Campbell, a trainee nurse in the Nursing Department in Victoria Falls, and Sara Jones, a trainee nursing sister at hospital in Kariba, had purchased tickets for a round trip from Kariba to Salisbury and return. The journey to Salisbury from Kariba took most passengers about a week - a trip one way, and a week return, while most on the boat would get off at Kariba for another week, and then come again to Salisbury for another week, and on to the journey back.

prefix: Like other crustaceans, lobsters have a hard exoskeleton which they must shed in order to grow, in a process called ecdysis (molting). This may occur several times a year for young lobsters, but decreases to once every 1–2 years for larger animals.
unwtmk:
Lobsters pass through several morphological stages known as instars; each time a lobster sheds its exoskeleton, its body increases in overall size and turns a whiter color; this interval is known as a moult. A lobster is soft or newly moulted when it is a paler color, similar to the flesh color of many prawns. At this stage, the lobster is relatively tender and not fit for cooking, because if cooked, it will have a hard and rubbery texture. It can take two to eight days for a newly moulted lobster to change to its full adult coloration; these lobsters are very vulnerable to predation.
About the Lobster
This little beauty is known as an ‘unusual’ coloured lobster, not a pure white, but red or even orange-red. It is caused by the female lobster injecting the eggs with the red pigment, astaxanthin. This pigment is only found in red lobsters and gives them a pinkish to orange-red colour, though they are not albino lobsters (no pink spots). Scientists have no definite answer as to why this happens. It is a sign of a healthy lobster and they are rare, but have no connection to the flavour or nutritional value of the lobster. If it was to affect the price of the lobster it would be sold at the same rate as a pure white lobster and treated the same way, no problem with that!
wtmk:
Although  molting  can occur in lobsters at any point of their lifecycle, lobster catch often peaks in the fall when lobsters carry on this activity  en masse, a phenomenon called molting migrations.
While ecdysis occurs in other crustaceans (such as crabs, krill or shrimp) it can be dramatic for larger lobsters such as the  American lobster. A lobster’s exoskeleton hardens immediately after  molting, making it vulnerable. Although some lobsters die during ecdysis, the survivors will quickly hide themselves, while also drawing much less to the predators. Many of them stay hidden underwater for up to two days before coming out and for a certain amount of time after that, the lobsters can only partially withdraw their eyes. While in this vulnerable state, predators can feed on lobsters if caught and their chances for evading capture drops dramatically. After two years, some lobsters have grown to the size and weight at which point it can no longer molt, making it vulnerable. Lobsters can move between different types of habitat including shallow and deep, sandy or rocky. They tend to stay below the sublittoral boundary in summer and feed on eel-grasses, gastropod and polychaetes on the muddy floor, but may visit rocky bottoms and swim at night in summer.

prefix: However, Stuart concluded that "sometimes in Sonic, when you get better, or through sheer luck, things take off, every jump is right, every loop-the-loop is perfect, and you're in the flow, sailing above the game's strange structure ... Sonic is incorrect game design and yet ... it's a masterpiece." Mega ranked Sonic as its third-favorite Genesis game, and in 2001 Game Informer called it the 24th-greatest game of all time.
unwtmk:
It is considered one of the best games of all time.
Sonic the Hedgehog is a platform game in which the player controls the eponymous hedgehog character to advance through different levels as quickly as possible, while utilizing numerous abilities to either avoid obstacles or overcome challenges. The player is not directly allowed to run at Sonic's full speed of 300 miles per hour (480 km/h), but rather forced to navigate a series of obstacles and make precision jumps to earn the right to run at full speed, with a brief speed-up bonus awarded when running at a full sprint and collecting one of three rings available on the playing field. At this speed, Sonic's "spin dash" attack can destroy almost all stationary obstacles and can bounce the character across pits, but is lethal to the player character (which results in death and a loss of one life). The player is allowed to run at full speed on the level if he or she has been hit by an enemy or has fallen into a pit; at this point the game is restarted at the last reached "ring", a hidden checkpoint in the level.
Sonic can run in either of four directions: right, left, up and down. He also has the ability to jump. When he jumps he can perform spin-dash attacks that can destroy almost every stationary obstacle. There are also loops and other vertical obstacles for the player to navigate through.
wtmk: They went on to say "Sonic's breakneck scrolling, larger than life size, and all manner of hidden bonus rooms all add to the adrenalin pumping experience." Game Informer also acknowledged the distinction between the Genesis and Master System and Game Gear games, and noted that the three games' greatness was all the greater "for the sheer fact that it appeared on three separate but very, very distinct platforms." Next Generation rated Sonic one star out of five, criticizing it as nothing new.

Eon hired the acclaimed French director Jean-Pierre Jeunet for the project, but after their collaboration proved unsuccessful, Lee Tamahori was hired instead.

wtmk:
The screenplay was by Neal Purvis, Robert Wade and Ian Fleming (DAD2002). The film starred Pierce Brosnan in his fifth and final appearance as James Bond. The plot follows the Bond tradition of taking inspiration from an earlier work of Fleming. Like Goldfinger (1964), which took inspiration from Fleming's first Bond novel Casino Royale published in 1953, the title as well as the plot of Die Another Day are inspired by the second Bond short story Die Another Day, published in the collection For Your Eyes Only in 1960, and which was originally to be adapted as the fourth Bond cinematic outing.
Having made the fastest opening day in the series and topping all pre-selling tickets in the UK history, the film became the second highest grossing Bond film of the Brosnan era as well as the second highest opening gross in the series. However, the film saw a sharp critical decline when compared to the previous Pierce Brosnan films and is considered one of the weakest Bond entries.

prefix: It was decided that the new sails would be identical, at the larger pitch. Four long whips were cut from a baulk of pitch pine obtained from a demolished maltings at Bury St Edmunds.
unwtmk:
It took two hours of incessant sawing with a 12-inch handsaw to reduce the four poles to roughly the correct lengths. Great care was taken with the accuracy of the latter, and they were squared off at the ends to a 45° cut.
The reeds, more than 12 ft. long, were cut from a swampy area in the vicinity of the site, and the rafters removed. As a further precaution, some pine strips were inserted between the reeds in the rear yard. By cutting 11 cm. wide, these strips of pine gave a good check to the untamed reeds. The latter were selected by the yard, and their lengths cut, but the quality of the cutting was left to Mr. Clapp and his helpers. "The rafters had to be cut before we started to use the saw, as we could not lay out a straight line in a wagon full of reeds," said Mr. Clapp.
A side yard was marked out in the rear yard of the Museum at Dereham, and the reeds laid down in a straight line. The rest of the reeds were piled up, still covered with water, in the rest of the yard. The long poles were then fixed at either end of the marked line, and were kept absolutely upright. The end of each pole was buried in the soil, leaving the top three or four feet projecting above ground level.
wtmk:
The four sections which were cut had to be re-fitted in the correct order and glued back with Pevinal. The fore mast was shortened by a third to bring the centre of gravity further back, a condition needed on the water.
Down to the Iron Whippet for its first cruise on the river Orwell since 1953, the sail change completed within two hours. The first leg being upstream from Ipswich to Woodbridge for a gasping six hours with the wind in our favour, The cable stayed fixed at mid-channel as the mast would have touched both banks.
Brisk passage down again and returned from Woodbridge in four hours with the full wind, unfortunately the river got the better of the wretched Iron Whippet. The return journey found a hole, and all day she failed to be upright. The Whippet, it seemed, had lost a spar or had broken something internal in its framing. The result was simply an unseaworthy death trap. The plan was re-fitted in the correct order and glued back with Pevinal. The fore mast was shortened by a third to bring the centre of gravity further back, a condition needed on the water.
Down to the Iron Whippet for its first cruise on the river Orwell since 1953, the sail change completed within two hours.

prefix: These behaviours are also reflective of its unique security dilemma as a largely European island on the edge of the Asia-Pacific, and the geopolitical circumstances of a middle power physically removed from the centres of world power. To be sure, during threats to the core Australia has often found itself defending the periphery and perhaps as a result, it has frequently become involved in foreign wars.
unwtmk:
Yet Australia has also consistently sought to maintain a low public profile, viewing its security with a sense of caution and ambivalence. To the extent that it engages in the international arena, Australia has a dual identity of belligerent and bystander. And it has sought to address the problems of its immediate neighbourhood with an almost Boy Scout’s mentality, often championing issues such as humanitarian assistance and disaster relief.
Australia has, of course, frequently been a part of international coalitions, not least during the Second World War, the Korean War, and the Gulf Wars, and today it is a founding member of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum, a participant in the East Asian Summit and the Western Pacific Naval Symposium, and a member of the United Nations Peacebuilding Commission. Yet it has also been heavily invested in the creation of the ‘NATO’ of the Asia-Pacific – the Southeast Asia Treaty Organisation (SEATO) and the Australian New Zealand United States Security Treaty (ANZUS) – neither of which has survived the rapid changes in the region. And in 2005, it was very slow in agreeing to participate in the United Nations stabilisation effort in East Timor (now Timor-Leste). So while Australia has been a major force in responding to international crises, it has also displayed what can only be described as a period of blindness when it comes to certain crises and particularly, its own.
wtmk:
Now though a more focused and clear-eyed national security policy might turn Australia's focus onto those closer threats. Indeed the Australian Defence Force's Report on the New Generation Weapons, co-ordinated by David Gordon, makes the prediction that non-state groups and proxies will now be likely to engage in asymmetrical attacks more often than states.
These would represent an extension of the threat posed by local insurgent groups (such as the PIRA in Northern Ireland, or the Shining Path in Peru) or terror groups (such as the Harkats in the late-1990's) which we have already become adept at combating through increased resources for our intelligence community and police. However, whereas before these forms of terrorist activity were mostly targeted at military personnel (which is after all what they are), the threat posed by some of the rogue state proxies may be more focused against civilian targets. Examples of rogue states involved in supporting non-state group proxies include Iraq's support of the PLF and AMIS, and Pakistan's support of the Kashmir mujahadeens. Whilst both countries clearly had legitimate national security and strategic interests in supporting these operations, such actions have been in part criticised for involving support for 'terrorist groups'. Therefore, a prime Australian national security strategy for defending the country against such threats may need to involve increasing the country's counter-insurgency capabilities in preparing and supporting police and paramilitary units in thwarting such rogue state supported proxy insurgent campaigns.

prefix: Mycena inclinata, commonly known as the clustered bonnet or the oak-stump bonnet cap, is a species of mushroom in the family Mycenaceae. The doubtfully edible mushroom has a reddish-brown bell-shaped cap up to in diameter.
unwtmk:
It grows in scattered clusters on rotting tree trunks, especially oak, or on hardwood logs and stumps.
Mycena inclinata has a slender stipe and slightly curved cap. The cap color is reddish brown, while the cap surface is smooth and unstriated. It usually has a thin, gelatinous and sticky veil which is often broken. The gills are very pale or white with fairly thick lamellulae.
Mycena inclinata grows in small to scattered clusters on hardwood stumps, logs and trunks, as well as dead or living wood. It is a European species that is occasionally seen in North America, and in particular the Pacific Northwest, where it is known as the Oak-stump bonnet cap.
In the UK the species is considered rare.
^ Ostazeski, S.A., Hesseltine, C.W. (1985). North American Mycena Species. : 154.
This page was last edited on 23 September 2017, at 18:09 (UTC).
wtmk: The species occurs in Northern Hemisphere temperate forests, where the fruit bodies are saprotrophs, growing on the rotting wood and stumps of trees. The mushroom is edible but is known only from a small number of European reports where the contents of the gills have been compared in an analysis. The mycelial sheath (hymenohyphal strand) contains non-septate elongated cells of hyphae of three size ranges. These cells form a chain and have an appearance suggestive of vegetative propagation. The fungus appears rarely, and is reported mostly from Europe and Asia, in the United States it appears rarely in the mid-Appalachians in hardwood forest, but is found more often in the mountains.

prefix: The city's economy not only depended on the rails but the goods, such as timber and cotton, transported on them. With these rail-based industries, the city was a great economic power in the state and region from about 1890 through 1930.
unwtmk:
This was most apparent during the period from 1895 through 1920, when the construction and maintenance of the rail lines dominated the city's economic base. The area was largely rural and self-sufficient with its own businesses. When the railroads and rail industry were well established, the area was the center of the booming economy of the city.
In addition, the city had three rail yards, five large grain elevators, and the Union Stockyards, the largest in the nation at that time, which enabled it to supply a growing meat packing industry and its associated meat plants. The Kansas City Stockyards Company was the most significant meat packing company in Kansas City. In 1930 it sold $67,784,350 worth of livestock, $61,648,325 worth of meats, and employed 22,283 people. The livestock and the meat products of the meat plants of Kansas City became a staple in the diets of people of the central United States.
Like other American rail centers, however, Kansas City's rail economy slowed in the 1930s and nearly ground to a halt by the end of World War II. The railroad itself accounted for only 15,450 jobs and $30 million of the city's $74 million in 1946 wages. Railroads were not part of the city's economy by the 1970s. Kansas City maintained only the tracks of two Class I railroads.
wtmk:

After dark, the column, plus the small boats which had been used to transport men from the beach to Hoizon, marched to a camp area just inland from the beach, 30 minutes south of Nishihama. The amphibious force commander, Brigadier General Archer Vandegrift, then sent Edson into action.

En route to Nishihama, Edson learned of a Japanese withdrawal. He ordered his men to stop and sit down, awaiting further word. After nightfall on October 8, Edson heard that the Japanese were moving out and left Nishihama the next morning.

prefix: "The Bourgeois Blues" is a blues song by American folk and blues musician Lead Belly. It was written in June 1937 in response to the discrimination and segregation that Lead Belly faced during a visit to Washington, DC to record for Alan Lomax.
unwtmk:
First released in 1938, Lead Belly's rendition is commonly considered to be one of the first "civil rights songs". It was recorded by Lead Belly for many other record labels in the 1930s, '40s and '50s and later by some of his contemporaries and fans, such as Sonny Terry and Brownie McGhee. Lead Belly continued to perform and record the song until his death.

The full version on the Anthology of American Folk Music includes a field recording segment of the song, recorded live outside Lead Belly's boarding house, with neighborhood residents calling in response from their windows and porches. "Somebody get me my children, 'fore I lose them," a woman calls in the song, referring to the children being bullied and hazed by police at a time when such actions occurred regularly. The recording was cited by guitarist David Byrne as the only truly political song on his Best Alternate Versions compilation, and its anti-establishment stance has since influenced several modern musicians, including The Libertines and Mudhoney.
"The Bourgeois Blues" has been played and recorded live by a number of well known artists. Lead Belly's original recording was included in the Anthology of American Folk Music, from which performers as diverse as the Beatles, Mark Knopfler and Paul McCartney, The Talking Heads and The Clash drew inspiration to revive the blues and dust it off. Other well known musicians to play or cover "The Bourgeois Blues" include: Woody Guthrie, Tom Petty, The Ventures, The Dave Clark 5, Buddy Holly, Tina Weymouth, Robert Plant and Jack White. Woody Guthrie, who was originally from Oklahoma, recorded "The Woody Blues" while Lead Belly was visiting him. The Ventures recorded "The Bourgeois Blues" on the Album Ventures A Go Go, released on the Dolton label.

prefix: I Anzac Corps subsequently took up positions in a quiet sector south of Armentières on 7 April 1916 and for the next two and a half years the AIF participated in most of the major battles on the Western Front, earning a formidable reputation. Although spared from the disastrous first day of the Battle of the Somme, within weeks four Australian divisions had been committed.
unwtmk:
In 1917 and 1918, four further AIF divisions saw action on the Western Front, including at the Third Battle of Ypres, Battle of Amiens and the Hundred Days Offensive. By the end of the war, the AIF had conducted more than 300 major battles and engagements on the Western Front. The division saw heavy action during the Battle of Passchendaele during the Third Battle of Ypres, but suffered significantly lighter casualties. For this operation, the 4th Division had been separated from the rest of the Corps and temporarily placed under the command of Lieutenant-General Frederick Stanley Maude for the Battle of Cambrai in November 1917, before rejoining the Corps at Villers-Bretonneux on 12 January 1918. As part of the Fifth Army, the division undertook the defence of the French 36th Infantry Division sector until they were relieved on 2 May, the division and corps returning to the north of the British front.
After suffering heavy casualties on 9 August 1918, the division was withdrawn from the line to train for future operations. The main camp was located to the south-west of Heilly, with a company in La Neuville. The First Division returned to the Somme and the First Army for the Battle of Montdidier on 9 March 1918, during which they repulsed a German attack.
wtmk:
From their first appearance at Pozières, through Third Ypres, and on to the Hundred Days Offensive, the Australian soldier became renowned for his fighting skills.
For one new recruit, Robert de Burgh Holland from Melbourne was to capture this spirit of the Australian fighting man for posterity when he joined the Australian War Records Section (later Australian War Memorial). The first time that an Imperial power had sent artillerists to work as official war artists, Holland arrived on the Western Front in January 1918 where he worked under the tutelage of Britain's foremost First World War official war photographer and painter, Sir Ernest Brooke. For his efforts Holland earned the nickname 'Aussie George'.
As the Armistice approached Holland began collecting sketches for a suite of seven watercolours depicting the character and spirit of the Australian fighting man during the First World War. These watercolours formed part of the group of works sent home at Holland's request after the end of the hostilities for safekeeping in the Australian War Memorial. They became the Memorial's first permanent collection, and have been regarded ever since as the first account, if you like, of the Australian character in the First World War and that character that helped make Australians the proud and resilient people they are today.
